  const left = barChart(z, ["z₀", "z₁", "z₂", "z₃"], 10, "#0096ff", "z input to softmax");
  const right = barChart(a, ["a₀", "a₁", "a₂", "a₃"], 1, "#C00000", "softmax(z)");
  return html`&lt;div style="display:flex;flex-wrap:wrap;gap:16px;align-items:flex-start;"&gt;${left}${right}&lt;/div&gt;`;
}






As you move the sliders, three things stand out.

The exponential in the numerator magnifies small differences in the scores. A score that is only a little larger than the others can end up with a much larger probability.
The output values always sum to one.
The softmax spans all of the outputs. Changing one score, say \(z_0\), changes every probability \(a_0\) through \(a_3\), because they all share the same denominator. This is unlike ReLU or sigmoid, which take a single input to a single output.



The Cost with an Indicator Function
For a single example the cross-entropy loss is \(-\log(a_j)\) when the true label is \(y = j\). Only the line matching the target contributes; the others are zero. To write the whole-dataset cost compactly, introduce an indicator function that is 1 when its condition holds and 0 otherwise,
\[
\mathbf{1}\{y = j\} =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if } y = j, \\
0 & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\]
The cost is then the average loss over all \(m\) examples,
\[
J(\vec{w}, b) = -\frac{1}{m} \sum_{i=1}^{m} \sum_{j=1}^{N} \mathbf{1}\{y^{(i)} = j\} \, \log \frac{e^{z^{(i)}_j}}{\sum_{k=1}^{N} e^{z^{(i)}_k}}.
\]
The inner indicator picks out the single term for the correct class of each example, so this really is just the average of the per-example losses.


Two Ways to Implement It in TensorFlow
Here the two implementations from earlier are run on a real four-class dataset built with scikit-learn’s make_blobs.

